{"cursor":"7839","size":15,"audio":[],"cat":[],"tmpl":[],"currentlang":"en","linknr":349,"url":"Formal_science","article":"\n\n'Formal sciences' are disciplines concerned with formal systems, such as logic,\nmathematics, statistics, theoretical computer science, information theory, game\ntheory, systems theory, decision theory, and portions of linguistics.\n\nWhereas natural sciences and other sciences like social sciences, behavioral\nsciences, and cognitive science seek soundness of scientific theory with respect\nto observations in order to successfully predict and perhaps accurately explain\nphenomena in the external world, the formal sciences are concerned with the\ninternal properties of formal systems, especially definitions of terms and rules\ngoverning inferences.\n\nFormal sciences sometimes aid constructing, assessing, and testing scientific\ntheories and scientific models, however, by revealing inconsistencies or invalid\nforms of inference.\n","recorded":1362124259,"portal":[],"list":[],"links":"350","instances":["physics","computer_science","soil_study","philosopher"],"pdf":["http://www.maths.unsw.edu.au/~jim/philosophersstone.pdf"],"categories":["Formal sciences|"],"headings":["History","Differences from other forms of science","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"tags":[["abstraction","mathematics"],["abstraction","computer_science"],["james_franklin","philosopher"],["plasma","physics"],["pedology","soil_study"],["abstraction","mathematics"],["abstraction","computer_science"],["james_franklin","philosopher"]],"image":["http://en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Office-book.svg/30px-Office-book.svg.png","http://bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"related":[